# access-manager

- **Module:** `github.com/dtorabi/access-manager` with **module root `go/`**. Read [AGENTS.md](AGENTS.md) for layout and workflow.
- **Security:** No secrets in code or committed config. Prefer 127.0.0.1 for dev. Do not suggest public `0.0.0.0` without auth and an explicit requirement.
- **Library boundary:** Under **`go/`**: keep `internal/access` and `internal/store` free of chi/HTTP imports. Put HTTP-only code in `internal/api` and wiring in `cmd/server`. Target future `go/pkg/...` for APIs other projects can import; avoid coupling core logic to the router.
- **Changes:** Match existing style; avoid unrelated refactors. For small fixes, proportionate checks only.
- **No unused code:** Do not add functions, methods, or interfaces that are not called or used anywhere in the current codebase. If a reviewer suggests adding speculative code (e.g. "consider implementing X for future use"), defer it to a ticket and reply on the review thread instead of adding dead code. The only exception is when building a module whose public API is defined by a plan — in that case, reference the plan in a code comment (e.g. `// See plan/phase-N/Txx.md`).
- **Tests:** Non-trivial behavior changes need **automated tests** (unit or integration) in the same PR. Pure wiring-only edits are the exception; when in doubt, add a test.
- **Branching:** When starting work on a new ticket or task, **create a topic branch** from up-to-date `main` **before making any file changes** (see [docs/branching.md](/docs/branching.md) for naming: `author/prefix/description`, all lowercase, e.g. `danyal/feature/t35-list-filtering`). Verify the current branch with `git branch --show-current`; if already on the wrong branch, stash, switch, create, and pop.
- **Git (AI default):** Do **not** run `git commit`, `git push`, or `gh pr create` unless the user explicitly asks. When a change set is ready, provide a **proposed commit message** (subject + optional body) and **PR description** matching **`.github/pull_request_template.md`** (**Summary**, **Ticket**, **Checklist**). The user runs git and `gh` locally.
- **After substantive changes:** Update **`go/README.md`** (and root **README.md** if repo layout/entrypoints changed); add CHANGELOG Unreleased if the file exists and the change is user-facing. Run **`make test`** from repo root or **`go test -race ./...`** from **`go/`**; use **`make lint`**, **`make cover`** when configured.
- **Before proposing or opening a PR (self-review):** Do at least one reviewer-style pass — see **[CONTRIBUTING.md](CONTRIBUTING.md)** (Pull requests → *Before you open a PR*). In short: (1) **`make test`** and **`make lint`** from repo root; **`go test -tags=e2e -count=1 -run '^$' ./e2e/...`** from **`go/`** when `go/e2e/` changed (compile-check tagged e2e package). (2) If you touched e2e docs or CI, align **README / CONTRIBUTING / go/README / `go/Makefile` / `.github/workflows/ci.yml`** on the **exact** `go test` flags. (3) No secrets or real tokens in the diff. (4) Skim for common review nits: **build tags** on `go/e2e` (non-test `.go` file must be included with `-tags=e2e`), **HTTP status before JSON decode** in tests, strict parsing in shell/JSON where IDs or booleans matter.
- **Future work:** Deferred work must map to a **GitHub issue** (or a tracked note on an existing issue/PR). Mention **`#…`** or `TODO(T36): ...` in comments when helpful (**`T36`** = plan file prefix under `plan/`). Extend an existing open issue when related; do not create a new issue for every tiny follow-up unless it is a distinct work item.
- **PR / review deferrals:** When a review comment (e.g. Copilot) is valid but you will **not** fix it in the current PR, reply on the thread that it will be addressed in **#… / Txx**, and add a **tracked note** under that umbrella’s **`plan/...`** file (Deliverables, Steps, or a short “Deferred from PR#…” bullet) so the follow-up is not lost.
- **GitHub:** If the user asks you to automate GitHub, use the **`gh`** CLI; prefer `gh` over raw `curl`. Otherwise supply copy-paste text for PRs/issues. See **[CONTRIBUTING.md](CONTRIBUTING.md)**.
- **PR ↔ issue (GitHub):** In the **PR description** (or a commit message), use **`Fixes #123`**, **`Closes #123`**, or **`Resolves #123`** so the PR shows on the issue timeline and merging to the default branch **auto-closes** the issue. Use **`Refs #123`** / **`See #123`** for a link without auto-close. Put this in the **Ticket** section of the PR body when applicable.
